{
  "title": [
    "resonator~"
  ],
  "description": "resonant complex one pole filter",
  "origin": "ELSE",
  "categories": [
    "Filters"
  ],
  "inlets": [
    {
      "messages": [
        {
          "type": "float/signal",
          "description": "central frequency in Hz"
        }
      ],
      "repeat": false
    },
    {
      "messages": [
        {
          "type": "signal",
          "description": "excitation signal"
        }
      ],
      "repeat": false
    },
    {
      "messages": [
        {
          "type": "float/signal",
          "description": "t60 decay time in ms (resonance)"
        }
      ],
      "repeat": false
    }
  ],
  "outlets": [
    {
      "messages": [
        {
          "type": "signal",
          "description": "resonator/filtered signal"
        }
      ],
      "repeat": false
    }
  ],
  "arguments": [
    {
      "type": "float",
      "description": "frequency",
      "default": "0"
    },
    {
      "type": "float",
      "description": "t60 decay time in ms",
      "default": "0"
    }
  ],
  "flags": [
    {
      "name": "-lop",
      "description": "set lowpass mode"
    },
    {
      "name": "-hip",
      "description": "set highpass mode"
    }
  ],
  "methods": [
    {
      "type": "clear",
      "description": "clears filter's memory"
    },
    {
      "type": "lop",
      "description": "set to lowpass mode"
    },
    {
      "type": "bp",
      "description": "set to bandpass mode"
    },
    {
      "type": "hip",
      "description": "set to highpass mode"
    }
  ],
  "body": "[resonator~] is just like [resonant~], but the resonance parameter is defined as resonance time in 't60'. It has 3 modes, the default is bandpass, which is like [resonant~], then you can also have lowpass (like [lowpass~]) and highpass (you guessed it, like [highpass~]). Note that a t60 value of 0 bypasses the input! For a bank of [resonator~] objects, see [resonbank~]. For another similar filter, see [resonator2~]."
}